 ('134', '24', '4', '1', 'en_us', '5', '', '{\"typeId\":\"5\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Welding\",\"slug\":\"welding\",\"postDate\":1470534600,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"parentId\":null,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p><strong>The Moore Tech Welding Program<\\/strong>&nbsp;requires persons who possess good manual dexterity, good eyesight, and good eye-to-hand coordination. They should be able to concentrate on detailed work for long periods of time. Because welding processes differ and are used for a wide variety of purposes, the equipment welders use and the skill levels vary.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Job descriptions vary from highly skilled manual welders who can use both gas and electric arc welding equipment, and welders who plan their work from drawings or other specifications to those of unskilled welding machine tenders who simply press a button to start a machine. Skilled welders know the characteristics of different types of metals and can weld in various positions. Welders who build ships and maintenance welders are examples of skilled welders.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>Moore Tech\\u2019s Welding Program is taught in one of the most extensive and complete welding labs in the south. It includes instruction in electric arc welding, plasma arc cutting, oxyacetylene cutting, oxyacetylene welding, (both ferrous, and nonferrous metals,) TIG (Tungsten Inert Gas) & MIG (Metal Inert Gas). The student is taught to identify and use various types of welding equipment, including the characteristics and techniques used in fabricating and assembling metal parts. An important aspect of the program is teaching the individual to read and follow directions.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>This program is designed for individuals who want to become professional welders. It provides the student with a working knowledge of the. The program also is designed to develop in the student the hands-on ability and confidence needed for successful employment within industry.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p>* Visit the&nbsp;<a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.mynextmove.org\\/profile\\/summary\\/51-4121.06\\\">O*NET<\\/a>&nbsp;link or go to the Dept. of Labor resource center to view the employment outlook for this program.<\\/p>\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n\\r\\n<p><a href=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.williamrmoore.org\\/sites\\/default\\/files\\/gainfulemployment\\/welding-2012-13.pdf\\\">Gainful Employment Information For This Program<\\/a><\\/p>\",\"32\":\"<p><strong><\\/strong><strong>What are the chances of getting a job upon graduation?<\\/strong> <strong>The placement rate for students<\\/strong><\\/p><p><strong>completing between July 1, 2012 and June 30, 2013 was 75%.<\\/strong> The U.S. Department of Education<br>requires colleges to report this data using the period shown above even though this is not the most current data<\\/p>\",\"24\":\"(CIP) Code: 48.0508 Welding Technology\\/Welder\",\"20\":\"\",\"31\":\"The Welding program is designed to be completed in one year. Nine ( 9) students completed the program between July 1, 2012 and June 30, 2013. Eighty-nine percent (89) of the graduating students completed the program within one year. This data includes all levels of program completers during the period including night certificates. \",\"30\":\"<p><strong><\\/strong><strong>The college does not participate in any type of loan programs.<\\/strong><\\/p><p>For students completing the program, the amount of loan debt for program graduates is shown below:<br><strong>Federal loans: none<br>Private education loans: none<br>Institutional financing plan:<\\/strong> none (Students pay for each trimester before beginning the next trimester.<\\/p>\",\"7\":\"95\",\"21\":\"Welding\",\"23\":\"One year (Three Trimesters)\",\"22\":\"Diploma\",\"27\":{\"new1\":{\"type\":\"question\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"question\":\"How much does the Welding program cost?\",\"answer\":\"<p><strong>Diploma program cost: Tuition and fees: $ 6480<\\/strong><\\/p>\"}},\"new2\":{\"type\":\"question\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"question\":\"What other costs are associated with this program?\",\"answer\":\"<p>Books and supplies: $0 (Books and supplies are included in tuition and fees.)<\\/p><p>Total fees depend on the elective courses taken. If Machine Shop is elected add $300 to the total.<br><strong>The college does not offer on-campus housing<\\/strong><\\/p>\"}},\"new3\":{\"type\":\"question\",\"enabled\":\"1\",\"fields\":{\"question\":\"What financial assistance is available for this program?\",\"answer\":\"<p>Full-time students may qualify for: U.S. Dept&nbsp;of Education Title IV (Pell) Grants and Tennessee Student Assistance Corporation (TSAC) Grants<\\/p>\"}}},\"5\":[\"21\",\"22\",\"23\"],\"18\":\"The Moore Tech Welding Program requires persons who possess good manual dexterity, good eyesight, and good eye-to-hand coordination. They should be able to concentrate on detailed work for long periods of time. Because welding processes differ and are used for a wide variety of purposes, the equipment welders use and the skill levels vary.\",\"6\":\"51-4121.06\",\"25\":\"(SOC) Code: 51-41210.06 Welders, Cutters, & Welder Fitters\",\"33\":\"The placement rate for students graduating in this program on July 25, 2013 was 93%. Graduating students were typically placed in jobs as Welders. Placement rates are based on graduates who were employed within 180 days of completion. Completers were tracked by using completion surveys with a response rate of 100%. The college is accredited by Council on Occupational Education and has been for over 40 years. \",\"19\":[\"103\"],\"3\":\"<iframe width=\\\"560\\\" height=\\\"315\\\" src=\\\"https:\\/\\/www.youtube.com\\/embed\\/-AS1BhfQBHI\\\" frameborder=\\\"0\\\" allowfullscreen><\\/iframe>\"}}', '2016-08-14 00:24:42', '2016-08-14 00:24:42', '8a029902-bac2-4592-9ebb